Falcon 9‚Äôs first stage booster previously supported SpaceX‚Äôs Crew-1 and Crew-2 missions, which launched astronauts to the International Space Station, and launch of SXM-8. Following stage separation, SpaceX will land Falcon 9‚Äôs first stage on the ‚ÄúA Shortfall of Gravitas‚Äù droneship, which will be located in the Atlantic Ocean. 

The Dragon spacecraft supporting this mission previously supported SpaceX‚Äôs 21st Commercial Resupply Services (CRS-21) mission. Dragon will separate from Falcon 9‚Äôs second stage about twelve minutes after liftoff and autonomously dock to the space station on Monday, August 30 at approximately 11:00 a.m. EDT, 15:00 UTC.

A live webcast of this mission will begin about 15 minutes prior to liftoff.
